05978nam a2200997Ia 9780271079264DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20202015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710792647 a10.1515/97802710792642doi  a(DE-B1597)584256  a(OCoLC)1262307186  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aCGN0070002bisacsh04a610.21 aCzerwiec, MK, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGraphic Medicine Manifesto /cMK Czerwiec, Ian Williams, Susan Merrill Squier, Michael J. Green, Kimberly R. Myers, Scott T. Smith. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b34 color/86 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGraphic Medicine ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Who Gets to Speak? The Making of Comics Scholarship -- t2. The Uses of Graphic Medicine for Engaged Scholarship -- t3. Graphic Storytelling and Medical Narrative -- t4. Graphic Pathography in the Classroom and the Clinic: A Case Study -- t5. Comics and the Iconography of Illness -- t6. The Crayon Revolution -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tComics Bibliography -- tAuthor Biographies and Acknowledgments -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis inaugural volume in the Graphic Medicine series establishes the principles of graphic medicine and begins to map the field. The volume combines scholarly essays by members of the editorial team with previously unpublished visual narratives by Ian Williams and MK Czerwiec, and it includes arresting visual work from a wide range of graphic medicine practitioners. The book’s first section, featuring essays by Scott Smith and Susan Squier, argues that as a new area of scholarship, research on graphic medicine has the potential to challenge the conventional boundaries of academic disciplines, raise questions about their foundations, and reinvigorate literary scholarship—and the notion of the literary text—for a broader audience. The second section, incorporating essays by Michael Green and Kimberly Myers, demonstrates that graphic medicine narratives can engage members of the health professions with literary and visual representations and symbolic practices that offer patients, family members, physicians, and other caregivers new ways to experience and work with the complex challenges of the medical experience. The final section, by Ian Williams and MK Czerwiec, focuses on the practice of creating graphic narratives, iconography, drawing as a social practice, and the nature of comics as visual rhetoric. A conclusion (in comics form) testifies to the diverse and growing graphic medicine community. Two valuable bibliographies guide readers to comics and scholarly works relevant to the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aComic books, strips, etc. 0aMedical carevCaricatures and cartoons. 0aMedicinevCaricatures and cartoons. 7aCOMICS & GRAPHIC NOVELS / Nonfiction / General.2bisacsh  aCzerwiec.  aGreen.  aIllness.  aMyers.  aSquier.  aWilliams.  acomics.  aculture.  adigital.  adisability.  afeminism.  agraphic.  ahealth.  ahumanities.  amedicine.  anarrative.  atrauma studies.  atrauma.  aunderground.  avisual.1 aCzerwiec, Mk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerrill Squier, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyers, Kimberly R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMyers, Kimberly R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmit